\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/nf.label}{Number field label}}
\begin{definition}\label{nf.label}
\uses{nf.degree,nf.discriminant,nf.signature}
Each (global) number field has a unique label of the form d.r.D.i where
<ul>
<li>\(d\) is the \hyperref[nf.degree]{degree};
<li>\(r\) is the real signature;  the full \hyperref[nf.signature]{signature} is therefore \([r,(d-r)/2]\);
<li>\(D\) is the absolute value of the \hyperref[nf.discriminant]{discriminant};
<li>\(i\) is the index, counting from 1.  This is in case there is more than one
  field with the same signature and absolute value of the
  discriminant: for example \href{/NumberField/4.0.1008.1}{4.0.1008.1} and \href{/NumberField/4.0.1008.2}{4.0.1008.2}.
</ul>
The discriminant portion of the label can take the form \(a_1\) e \(\epsilon_1\) \textit{ \(a}2\) e \(\epsilon_2\) \textit{ \(\cdots\) } \(a_k\) e \(\epsilon_k\) to mean the absolute value of the
discriminant equals \(a_1^{\epsilon_1}a_2^{\epsilon_2}\cdots a_k^{\epsilon_k}\).  The separators are the letter e and the underscore symbol.
\end{definition}


